# Detection Methodology

## Data Sources

* Windows Security Logs
* Event ID 4625 (Failed Logon)
* Winlogbeat Log Collection
* Kibana SIEM Correlation Rules

---

## Detection Query

```kql id="v9h1n3"
event.code: "4625" AND
winlog.event_data.LogonType: "10"
```

---

## Detection Logic

The detection rule identifies excessive failed RDP authentication attempts occurring within a short time period.

Indicators of brute force activity included:

* High frequency of failed logins
* Repeated targeting of the same username
* Remote Interactive logon attempts (Type 10)
* Rapid event generation consistent with automated tools

---

# Investigation Findings

## Observed Activity

* Hydra used to automate password-guessing attempts
* 124 failed logins recorded within 60 seconds
* Single account (`bfish`) repeatedly targeted
* No successful authentication observed
* SIEM correlation rule triggered immediately after the threshold exceeded

---

# Response Actions

## Containment

* RDP service temporarily disabled
* Source attack traffic isolated within the lab environment
* Security logs preserved for analysis

## Eradication

* Brute force activity terminated
* Target account reviewed for compromise
* Authentication monitoring increased

## Recovery

* RDP access restored after validation
* Password policies reviewed
* Monitoring continued after containment

---

# Recommendations

## Immediate Improvements

* Implement account lockout policies
* Restrict RDP access using firewall rules
* Enforce strong password requirements
* Enable multi-factor authentication (MFA)

---

## Long-Term Security Enhancements

* Deploy geolocation-based login restrictions
* Monitor for authentication spikes
* Limit external RDP exposure
* Use VPN access for remote administration

